                     <handDesc>
                        <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic"><locus from="9r" to="51v"/>
                           <seg type="script"><date>Mid-nineteenth/mid-twentieth century bulky
                                 script.</date></seg>
                           <seg type="ink">Black (on many folia brownish); vivid red.</seg>
                           <seg type="rubrication">Divine names; directives for the ministers;
                              titles of books to be read; elements of the punctuation signs;
                              elements of the Ethiopic numerals. On the incipit page of <ref target="#p1_i1">Text 1</ref>, <locus target="#8r"/> two first lines
                              of each column are rubricated. Rubrication has been carefully executed
                              in the main hand, probably along with the writing of the main
                              text.</seg>
                           <desc>Careful but irregular writing; by a poorly trained scribe. Broad, upright
                              or slightly right sloping script. Downstrokes slanted irregulary,
                              horizontal tops. Rectangular letter shapes, but irregular and poorly
                              drawn. Starting from approximately <locus target="#47"/> the handwriting
                              becomes even less careful. On <locus from="50r" to="51r"/> the scribe
                              reduced the size of the script and accomodated on the pages more
                              written lines than the ruling allows. It cannot be excluded that more
                              than one scribe participated in copying. </desc>
                        </handNote>
                     </handDesc>


